the guest bathroom is also the girl’s bathroom and i love that it feels playful but also grown up. ✨ i love the vintage rugs that used to be in my grandparents home in alabama (30 min from us now!), makes me feel like they are always with us. we repurposed the vanity that was here before with fresh hardware and plumbing. the mirror is a medicine cabinet that holds bows and skincare. :)

on this day 18 years ago at 7:30 pm in atlanta ga at king plow we exchanged vows. we were surrounded by family and friends that have loved us well over the past 18 years.

within our first tender years of marriage we bought our first house, moved three times, had a baby girl, lost both of sam’s parents, and walked through the fires of divorce within our family. we quickly tasted how bitter and sweet life can be.

the following years were full of similar highs and lows (another baby girl!) but my choice in the flat iron loving emo boy with a creative big heart proved to be a wise one. by the grace of God we have grown together, wiped each other’s tears, laughed our butts off, worked harden than it seems humanly possible, and we still love and respect each other. 

sam has been a steady anchor against life’s brutal waves. he points me to Jesus, he makes me breakfast (and many other meals!), he is tender and compassionate, loving and kind. i trust him more than any other human and he has shown me what safe feels like. well i don’t want to ruin my makeup before our date so i’ll just say, cheers to 18 and a lifetime more. i love you sam. you’re my favorite. ❤️

i recently turned 42 and here are 42 things i have learned over the years! 1. put God first and the rest will fall into place 2. journaling is one of our greatest teachers and tools 3. our environments matter and shape our lives 4. to have a friend you have to be a friend 5. sometimes you have to go first 6. leadership is the highest responsibility that comes with the highest cost but it’s important 7. “behave in a way that even if people bad talk you others won’t believe it” 8. forgiveness does not mean forgetting 9. forgive anyways 10. “first one in last one out” 11. “love many trust few always paddle your own canoe” 12. be the friend you want to have 13. “you are the equivalent of the 5 people you spend the most time with - choose wisely” 14. alcohol isn’t necessary to have fun and it’s not for everyone 15. be the mentor you needed 16. believe the best 17. holding your tongue is almost always a good idea 18. you never know what someone is walking through - show mercy 19. what you say about others says more about you 20. pray more than you think you need to 21. “more is caught than taught” 22. be the first to say you’re sorry 23. a good meal and a good cry solve many problems 24. when in doubt get outside 25. don’t trust people that constantly trash others 26. it’s better to be lonely than in bad company 27. lipstick helps 28. make your bed 29. get dressed 30. buy fewer and buy quality 31. have your own back 32. don’t let others put you in a box 33. brush your teeth 34. buy organic when you can 35. choose kindness even when it stings 36. tell people you love them 37. turn the other cheek 38. “it’s a joy to overlook an offense” 39. make sure no one’s voice is louder than God’s 40. hard work is always worth it 41. develop a resiliency that makes you unstoppable 42. the four agreements: “be impeccable with your word, always do your best, do not make assumptions, don’t take things personally” #42for42

rainy sunday in the kitchen 💕 my top five kitchen design tips: 1. hire a designer to help with flow - a cabinet designer can do this for you also! 2. having your cabinets go to the ceiling makes for less dust catching and draws your eye up. 3. use more drawers than cabinets! better for storage and easier to access and organize. 4. if you can, a pot filler is such a versatile and functional addition! 5. i love a mix of open shelving and concealed. you can display your favorite things and keep everything else hidden.

let me know if you have any questions! #kitchendesign #englishcountrystyle #englishkitchen #kitchenremodel #kitchen

Easter Photo Dump 💕 Thankful for our family and the gift of hope. Our pastor encouraged us to join him in reading 1 Peter 3-9 daily. Here’s what it says: 

“Blessed be the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ! According to his great mercy, he has caused us to be born again to a living hope through the resurrection of Jesus Christ from the dead, to an inheritance that is imperishable, undefiled, and unfading, kept in heaven for you, who by God’s power are being guarded through faith for a salvation ready to be revealed in the last time. In this you rejoice, though now for a little while, if necessary, you have been grieved by various trials, so that the tested genuineness of your faith—more precious than gold that perishes though it is tested by fire—may be found to result in praise and glory and honor at the revelation of Jesus Christ. Though you have not seen him, you love him. Though you do not now see him, you believe in him and rejoice with joy that is inexpressible and filled with glory, obtaining the outcome of your faith, the salvation of your souls.”

homemade flour tortillas!! these are an absolute game changer for taco night. from @magnolialeatherworks :

Combine 3 cups all purpose flour, 1 teaspoon salt, 1 teaspoon baking powder. Mix well with dough hook in a stand mixer. 

Combine 1 cup of warm water with 1/3 cup oil (I use avocado oil, but any oil or even melted butter will do. Olive oil isn’t the best because it leaves a heavier flavor.)

Pour water into flour mixture and mix on medium with your dough hook for about 1 minute. 

Once dough begins to form, slow mix speed to low and mix for an additional minute or so. 

After your dough is smooth, place it into a lightly floured surface and divide into 16 equal portions (about 45g each if you have a kitchen scale). Round each portion into a ball and then press flat-ish. Cover with a kitchen towel and let rest for AT LEAST 15 minutes. 

I usually go ahead and cook my tacos while the dough is resting. 

After the rest period, heat up a pan on medium.  If you use cast iron (which you should!) let it get nice and warmed up before using. 

While your pan is heating up start pressing the dough flat. I use a small pastry roller to help.  You want the dough pressed very thin - as thin as possible without tearing the dough. 

Oil your pan and place the tortilla in the center. Lightly salt the side facing up and start pressing your next tortilla. Let the tortilla cook for about 45 seconds or until bubbles begin to form. Flip the tortilla and lightly salt this side as well. Let this side cook for about 45 seconds. 

Bubbles on both sides of the tortilla should be slightly golden browned. If they are dark or black, turn your heat down. Also, be sure not to over cook as this will make the edges of your tortillas hard and brittle. If you have to, err on the side of undercooking. 

As you finish cooking each tortilla, put them on a plate and cover with a kitchen towel. This will steam the tortillas so that they’re nice and soft when you’re done cooking!

original recipe by @thecafesucrefarine ❤️❤️❤️

this is our family’s favorite gluten free pumpkin bread recipe! adapted from down east maine.

Gluten Free Pumpkin Bread

 You will need: 

 1/2 (15 ounce) can pumpkin puree

 2 eggs

1/2 cup vegetable oil

1/3 cup water

1-1/2 cups white sugar

1-3/4 cups pamela’s baking mix

2 teaspoon ground cinnamon

1 teaspoon all spice

 Method:

 Preheat oven to 350. Grease one 8.5” inch loaf pan.

 In a mixer, cream together pumpkin puree, eggs, oil, water and sugar until well blended.

 In a separate bowl, whisk together baking mix, cinnamon, and all spice. Stir the dry ingredients into the pumpkin mixture until just blended. Pour into the prepared pan.

 Bake for about 50 minutes in the preheated oven. Done when toothpick inserted in center comes out clean.  No one will know this pumpkin bread is gluten-free. It is so moist and delicious and perfect warm out of the oven with a little butter on top. Enjoy!

2/30 nurturing home! the big five in the morning. doing these five things every day will keep your home running so much smoother. some of these i learned from the fly lady method! she has a great app you can use! 

1. get dressed! this makes you so much more productive, even if it’s getting dressed in workout clothes.

2. make all of the beds. everything feels less chaotic with made beds. kids can help too!

3. toilets + sinks! @the_flylady calls it the swish and swipe method where you clean your vanity and toilets every morning.

4. start a load of laundry. load a day keeps the 👹 away.

5. unload the dishwasher from the night before!

that’s it! do you do these? any you are working on making a habit? if you’re like me it’s going to take a couple of weeks to get into maintenance mode but i’m ready!

*mid life thoughts* i was talking with a friend last week about the temptation as you get older to become bitter - especially for women. 

so easy to look at your life and all the demands and messy people and hard life things and feel disappointed, jaded, resentful, etc etc. you look in the mirror and some days you’re like “who even is this?” you don’t know what’s cool anymore or how to dress or do your hair.

your’e tired which makes every other mentioned thing feel more exhausting and dare i say annoying. most of us have been hurt by people we love and betrayed by people we thought were friends. it’s a lot this life thing.

BUUUTTTTT if we can stay soft. if we can keep forgiving people and loving people and seeing our own need for grace when we are quick to judge or recoil or hide THAT is where the magic is. that’s the secret sauce. that’s all the stuff we learned in church lived out.

oh and i added a desk to bee’s room today if you’re wondering how these things connect.

if you’re 40+ and doing the work, i’d love to hear some words of encouragement/wisdom in the comments. i know there are people fighting to believe this all isn’t for nothing. 🩷🙏 thank you for sharing!

evolution of our kitchen! when the storm damage happened it was the first time i broke down in tears. the kitchen and back of the house were covered in insulation and rain as the weight of the water caused the ceilings to collapse. i wailed from the kitchen in the early morning hours all the way down the driveway to our tiny cottage. sam thought someone had died. the truth is the horror of the weight of our personal life mixed with an uncertain future and the reality of everything we had been through to that point came to a soul crushing blow. what had i done to our family was all i could think in that moment.

The truth was God spared our beautiful cabinets which we put in too early - so many things popped up that made order go haywire, He provided a way to find the snake and to elevate the ceiling which looks 372829% better in my opinion. He sent @nataliecollier to help with the girls and @lovesdogs brought us dinner. My Dad was there before the sun had hardly broken through the clouds and Sam remained steady. It’s so easy in these big moments to lose all perspective and sometimes the tears need to flow and they did.

I’m so thankful for @huntandgathergoods for helping me to organize my thoughts and pushing me to splurge on the right things like the beautiful unlacquered brass faucet and pot filler. @costilicabinetry took my hopes and dreams and made them even better! I love the inset cabinets and tons of drawers which I now prefer!

Lights: @devolkitchens who helped us by saving the day with custom cords to work in the vaulted ceiling!
Counters: Circo white marble from @daltile 
Cabinets: feather down by @benjaminmoore and made by @costilicabinetry 
Light in breakfast nook: @alicepalmerco

SAVE THIS RECIPE! ❤️🎄 seven layer magic bars are my favorite! they take five minutes to make and you can customize however you want but here’s what i did:

SEVEN LAYER MAGIC BARS

Preheat oven to 350

Melt 10 T of butter and mix with 1 1/2 c of graham cracker crumbs and add to a 9x12 baking dish lined with parchment paper.

Layer on 1 c of chocolate chips, 1 c of butterscotch chips, 1 c of walnuts, 1 c of shredded coconut, top with a 14 oz can of condensed milk. 🤤 

Bake at 350 for 22-25 min 

I like to stick in the fridge once cool for several hours then cut into bars and top with @maldonsalt !

Let me know if you make them and Merry Christmas!!

sourdough biscuit recipe by @kingarthurbaking is fool proof! sam made these this morning for this frigid day and the entire house smelled like flaky butter heaven. have you tried making sourdough biscuits?

Buttery Sourdough Biscuits

Baking & Spices
2 tsp Baking powder
1 cup King arthur all-purpose flour, Unbleached
3/4 tsp Table salt

Dairy
8 tbsp Butter, unsalted

Prepared
1 cup Sourdough starter unfed/discard

Preheat the oven to 425°F, with a rack in the upper third. Grease a baking sheet, or line it with parchment.

Combine the flour, baking powder, and salt. Work the butter into the flour until the mixture is unevenly crumbly.

Add the starter, mixing gently until the dough is cohesive.

Turn the dough out onto a lightly floured surface (a piece of parchment works well), and gently pat it into a 6” round about 1”-thick.

Use a sharp 2 3/8” biscuit cutter to cut four rounds, cutting them as close to one another as possible. Gently push and pat the scraps into a 2 1/2” x 5” rectangle. Cut two more biscuits. Push and pat the remaining scraps into a 1”-thick biscuit; it’ll be slightly smaller than the others.

Place the sourdough biscuits onto the prepared baking sheet, leaving about 2” between them; they’ll spread as they bake.

Bake the sourdough biscuits in the upper third of your oven for 20 to 23 minutes, until they’re golden brown.

Remove the sourdough biscuits from the oven, and serve warm. Or cool completely, wrap in plastic, and store at room temperature for several days. Freeze, well-wrapped, for longer storage.
